In video games, =E2=80=9Cspeedrunning=E2=80=9D means completing a video gam=
e as fast as possible.=C2=A0
The world record speedrun for Super Mario 64, for example, belongs to the i=
nimitable cheesecheese, who beat the entire game in 1:37:50 while singing a=
nd responding to Twitch commenters.=C2=A0
Crypto has borrowed the term. It=E2=80=99s speedrunning the history of fina=
ncial markets. It=E2=80=99s speedrunning the history of governance.=C2=A0
Speedrunning is a catchy analogy, but it=E2=80=99s not quite perfect. For o=
ne, the best speedrunners play games that they=E2=80=99ve played thousands =
of times nearly flawlessly. For another, a speedrun video game ends at the =
same place that a game played at regular speed does.=C2=A0
What=E2=80=99s happening in crypto is different. No one is playing flawless=
ly. DeFi protocols (and CeFi entities) are doing many of the things that ha=
ve been done in the financial markets, making many of the same mistakes, an=
d learning many of the same lessons. DAOs are experimenting with the same g=
overnance models =E2=80=93 from direct democracy to representative democrac=
y, from direct shareholder vote to boards and management =E2=80=93 that loc=
al and national governments and corporations have tried. They=E2=80=99re ju=
st doing it really fast, compressing thousands of years of experiments into=
 less than a decade. In a piece by the same name for a16z, Andy Hall and Po=
rter Smith call it Lightspeed Democracy [https://substack.com/redirect/7464=
0d1e-a53e-4acf-af50-fa7fee8dd3d6?u=3D16283549]. That gets closer.=C2=A0
But the game shouldn=E2=80=99t end there. Just like online advertising star=
ted out as a copy-paste of print ads in the form of banner ads and evolved =
a richer and more sophisticated toolkit than would ever be possible offline=
, DAO governance can and should move beyond offline models.=C2=A0
We think that DAO governance should be more like a biological process [http=
s://substack.com/redirect/df270767-7a68-4166-bea6-bbde7e25a55f?u=3D16283549=
] run at internet speed: Internet-Native Evolutionary Governance.=C2=A0
The goal shouldn=E2=80=99t be to recreate offline governance, online, after=
 a period of trial-and-error. Internet-native organizations can=E2=80=99t a=
nd shouldn=E2=80=99t operate like geographic governments because they don=
=E2=80=99t face the same constraints. Once online governance models evolve =
past a certain point, they should be both different from and superior to of=
fline ones because of the speed, scale, granularity, programmability, compo=
sability, and unboundedness of the internet, and the blockchain.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
So what if we flipped the model?
What if we viewed the goal of DAO governance not as a way to agree on a lim=
ited number of decisions proposed from the top, but as a way to force peopl=
e to disagree on a whole host of decisions proposed by the community=E2=80=
=94so that larger groups that are unwieldy to coordinate could continue div=
iding into smaller, more efficient ones while building value for each other=
?=C2=A0
The real promise of DAO governance might be forking: using governance to ge=
t people to disagree and through the process, discover subcommunities where=
 they're aligned and create their own version of a project. Forking, in tha=
t sense, is the ultimate form of decentralization. And it enables governanc=
e to become the basis of social graphs where people find others who share t=
heir interests so they can pursue those.=C2=A0
In its simplest form, this kind of governance is just a process of decentra=
lized curation to incentivize a community to share and rank its preferences=
: good governance is just good user research. Through healthy dissent, gove=
rnance can be used to lead to the formation of subDAOs, and to encourage ev=
olutionary growth in the ecosystem. As non-crypto people know, forking lead=
s to procreation.
Viewed through that lens, governance mechanisms might become less defensive=
 =E2=80=93 focused less on protecting against hacks that threaten the entir=
e DAO =E2=80=93 and more offensive and fun =E2=80=93 focused more on govern=
ance as a means of entertainment, social discovery, and propagation.=C2=A0
To be clear, there=E2=80=99s no one-size-fits-all model for DAO governance,=
 and we=E2=80=99re not proposing that every DAO turn on its heels and encou=
rage forking, which should often be a last resort. What we=E2=80=99re propo=
sing is something else. Having different types of governance is a strength =
that lets different groups with different metrics optimize for what's impor=
tant to them according to their own system. As in nature, biodiversity prot=
ects the entire ecosystem.=C2=A0
There are challenges with this model, too, most notably that fragmentation =
might reduce liquidity, lower talent density, and add complexity. We=E2=80=
=99ll discuss these, and ways that DAOs might address them.=C2=A0
But if we=E2=80=99re experimenting and making mistakes anyway, we should ma=
ke productive mistakes. We should experiment in a direction that doesn=E2=
=80=99t lead to the same endpoint, and take advantage of new tools and less=
ened constraints to create new internet-native opportunities. Maybe one day=
, those new models will circle back and influence the way that humans coord=
inate offline. Maybe the lines between online and offline will blur to the =
point that governments and companies adopt new models born through this evo=
lution.=C2=A0
Today, we=E2=80=99ll explore the history, present, and a proposed future of=
 governance:=C2=A0
A Very Brief History of Governance=C2=A0
DAO Governance History and Challenges=C2=A0
Forking Governance=C2=A0
How Governance Might Work
Governance as a Social Network=C2=A0
Internet-Native Governance Evolution
To start our journey, let=E2=80=99s hop in the time traveler and head back =
to Ancient Greece.=C2=A0
A Very Brief History of Governance
First things first, what is governance?=C2=A0
Governance is the process of overseeing the control and direction of someth=
ing, like a government, business, or organization. It=E2=80=99s how groups =
of people decide what their group should do, and ensure that those decision=
s get enacted.=C2=A0
Humans have been trying to figure out governance since the beginning of tim=
e. In Pieces of the Action, Vannevar Bush wrote of organizations:=C2=A0
When Eve joined Adam, there was formed the first organization in history. I=
t is a simple one, yet its essential relations and the regulations governin=
g it have not even today been fully worked out. And ever since Eden, man ha=
s been building more and more complex organizations with which to carry on =
his affairs.
=E2=80=9CBuilding more and more complex organizations with which to carry o=
n our affairs=E2=80=9D is a good summary of the history of governance model=
s, but we=E2=80=99ll take a slightly longer walk. Most of us learned this s=
tuff in school, but it=E2=80=99s worth going over quickly in this context t=
o ground ourselves in the basics before we get weird.=C2=A0
For most of human history, people lived under autocratic rule, a system in =
which the power over the state is concentrated in the hands of one person: =
a king, queen, empress, emperor, or dictator. Whatever the autocrat decrees=
, the people must follow. Oligarchic rule, also popular throughout history,=
 feels similar to those being governed, but differs slightly in that the po=
wer is concentrated in the hands of a small group of people instead of one =
person. Autocratic rule was so popular early because it=E2=80=99s the simpl=
est form of governance =E2=80=93 one person decides and that=E2=80=99s it =
=E2=80=93 but history has shown that it has some uhhh flaws.=C2=A0=C2=A0
In the 5th Century BCE, the Ancient Greeks implemented a new form of govern=
ance (one practiced by tribal societies far earlier): democracy. In Ancient=
 Athens, one of democracy=E2=80=99s earliest homes, all citizens =E2=80=93 =
defined as native-born free men =E2=80=93 were required to take an active p=
art in government. Those who didn=E2=80=99t were fined and occasionally sha=
med with a splash of red paint. Athenian democracy worked [https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/6517135c-2198-43fa-8a47-9=
faf959d4a66?u=3D16283549] kind of li=
ke very long jury duty, in that each year:=C2=A0
Each year 500 names were chosen from all the citizens of ancient Athens. Th=
ose 500 citizens had to actively serve in the government for one year. Duri=
ng that year, they were responsible for making new laws and controlled all =
parts of the political process. When a new law was proposed, all the citize=
ns of Athens had the opportunity to vote on it. To vote, citizens had to at=
tend the assembly on the day the vote took place.=C2=A0
This form of governance, in which every citizen can vote on every decision,=
 is called direct democracy. Every citizen has their say, and then all must=
 follow what the majority decides. Direct democracy worked in Ancient Athen=
s because the scale was small and local, and even then, the Athenians elimi=
nated 70% of eligible voters (women, slaves, and immigrants) in order to ma=
intain a small group.=C2=A0
Even though the Ancient Greeks introduced democracy 2,500 years ago, and Ro=
me remained ruled by a republican government between 500 and 27 BC, autocra=
cy remained the dominant form of governance around the globe, with a few ex=
ceptions, until the United States Constitution came into force in 1789.=C2=
=A0
But while direct democracy worked well enough in the context of ruling a ci=
ty, the American experiment required a governance model that could handle 1=
3 colonies (and eventually 50 states) spread over a large area. As Hall and=
 Smith highlighted [https://substack.com/redirect/74640d1e-a53e-4acf-af50-f=
a7fee8dd3d6?u=3D16283549]:=C2=A0
As James Madison wrote in Federalist No. 14 [https://substack.com/redirect/=
04964607-681d-45f4-b913-104e8b0e33bd?u=3D16283549], =E2=80=9CIn a democracy=
, the people meet and exercise the government in person; in a republic, the=
y assemble and administer it by their representatives and agents. A democra=
cy, consequently, will be confined to a small spot. A republic may be exten=
ded over a large region.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
New contexts require new forms of governance. America=E2=80=99s Founding Fa=
thers built a republic, a form of representative democracy. The people elec=
t their representatives, and the representatives propose and pass legislati=
on.=C2=A0
Since then, the world has been on a bumpy but inexorable march towards repr=
esentative democracy.=C2=A0
A 2019 Pew Research report [https://substack.com/redirect/b34bbf14-14d1-426=
4-9e06-3de6c16efd1f?u=3D16283549] found that 57% of countries with populati=
ons over 500,000 are democratic. Modern democracy is representative democra=
cy.=C2=A0
Corporations, too, most often behave like representative democracies. Share=
holders elect the board, and the board hires and fires the management team,=
 who in turn hire and fire employees, and run the company day-to-day. Unlik=
e a national election, votes in the corporate setting are weighted by the n=
umber of shares each party holds, and the number of votes each of those sha=
res has.=C2=A0
While representative democracy has its issues, it appears less bad than pre=
vious forms of governance. As British Prime Minister Winston Churchill famo=
usly quipped, =E2=80=9CDemocracy is the worst form of government =E2=80=93 =
except for all the others that have been tried.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The whole history of governance has been a series of attempts to find solut=
ions that are less bad than their predecessors, and that best fit the conte=
xt and capabilities of their time. It would have been hard to imagine the r=
ise of national representative democracy before the invention of the printi=
ng press, for example. As Thomas Jefferson wrote, =E2=80=9Ca well informed =
electorate is a prerequisite to a democracy.=E2=80=9D
New tools, challenges, and constraint sets open the door for new models. Th=
e best system of governance for a large nation comprised of colonies connec=
ted by wagons and ships that needed to unify for economic and military reas=
ons might not be the ultimate form of human governance, or the one best-sui=
ted to internet-native organizations with very different goals, challenges,=
 and capabilities.
Governance can and should keep evolving. While it=E2=80=99s not easy for co=
untries or even companies to try new forms of governance, DAOs have the opp=
ortunity to rapidly experiment in ways that are only possible on the intern=
et.
DAO Governance History and Challenges=C2=A0
To date, however, DAO governance models have mostly been skeuomorphic versi=
ons of national and corporate ones. (For a primer on DAOs, check out Packy=
=E2=80=99s The DAO of DAOs [https://substack.com/redirect/745dfb98-ce46-41a=
7-97b0-d455ae071859?u=3D16283549].)
Most (if not all) governance mechanisms in crypto today revolve around some=
 sort of implementation of the one-token-one-vote concept, akin to token-we=
ighted direct democracy or shareholder democracy.=C2=A0
When DAOs have strayed from one-token-one-vote, mechanism designers have us=
ed novel on-chain capabilities to fortify the old model, as opposed to expe=
rimenting with entirely new ones. Among the more popular enhancements are:
One-Wallet-One-Vote: Akin to direct democracy, OWOV is an attempt to give a=
n equal vote to each member. There are challenges here, including the fact =
that less well-informed voters or those with less skin in the game have the=
 same voice as people with more knowledge or skin, and the fact that it=E2=
=80=99s often trivial for one person to set up multiple wallets to vote.=C2=
=A0
Quadratic Voting: Meant to decrease the voting power of large holders while=
 still giving them more of a voice than smaller holders, QV increases the c=
ost of each vote. One vote might cost one token, but two votes would cost f=
our, three would cost eight, and so on.=C2=A0
Proof of Participation: Proposed by people including Vitalik Buterin [https=
://substack.com/redirect/845268a6-fa92-4fa2-882a-dad2764fcce0?u=3D16283549]=
, PoP would only give votes to those who have actively participated in the =
DAO or protocol, which should make it harder and more expensive to wage gov=
ernance attacks.=C2=A0
There are others, but the majority of variations seem to focus mainly on de=
ploying protection layers to improve productivity and mitigate or delay the=
 effects of governance hacks =E2=80=93 so called Optimistic Governance [htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/66a2eff9-64d8-4350-99bd-c5dcdff5796f?u=3D1628354=
9] =E2=80=93 but not much more. All are important improvements, but they do=
n=E2=80=99t answer a key question: are the underlying governance frameworks=
 adopted able to incentivise virtuous behaviors while tackling complex task=
s?=C2=A0
Our guess is that, for the vast majority if not totality of DAO governance =
models out there, the answer is no.
