 d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 00-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 007.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/></svg></a=
></div></div></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">First things first, what is governance?&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 1em 0;">Governance is the process of overseeing the control and direction=
 of something, like a government, business, or organization. It&#8217;s how=
 groups of people decide what their group should do, and ensure that those =
decisions get enacted.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Humans have been trying to f=
igure out governance since the beginning of time. In </span><em>Pieces of t=
he Action</em><span>, Vannevar Bush wrote of organizations:&#160;</span></p=
><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0; margin-left: 1em;"><em><span>When Eve joined Adam, there was formed the =
first organization in history. It is a simple one, yet its essential relati=
ons and the regulations governing it have not even today been fully worked =
out. And ever since Eden, man has been </span><strong>building more and mor=
e complex organizations with which to carry on his affairs</strong><span>.<=
/span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">&#8220;Building more and more complex =
organizations with which to carry on our affairs&#8221; is a good summary o=
f the history of governance models, but we&#8217;ll take a slightly longer =
walk. Most of us learned this stuff in school, but it&#8217;s worth going o=
ver quickly in this context to ground ourselves in the basics before we get=
 weird.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>For most of human history, people lived und=
er </span><strong>autocratic</strong><span> rule, a system in which the pow=
er over the state is concentrated in the hands of one person: a king, queen=
, empress, emperor, or dictator. Whatever the autocrat decrees, the people =
must follow. </span><strong>Oligarchic</strong><span> rule, also popular th=
roughout history, feels similar to those being governed, but differs slight=
ly in that the power is concentrated in the hands of a small group of peopl=
e instead of one person. Autocratic rule was so popular early because it&#8=
217;s the simplest form of governance &#8211; one person decides and that&#=
8217;s it &#8211; but history has shown that it has some uhhh flaws.&#160;&=
#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>In the 5th Century BCE, the Ancient Greeks i=
mplemented a new form of governance (one practiced by tribal societies far =
earlier): </span><strong>democracy</strong><span>. In Ancient Athens, one o=
f democracy&#8217;s earliest homes, all citizens &#8211; defined as native-=
born free men &#8211; were required</span><em> </em><span>to take an active=
 part in government. Those who didn&#8217;t were fined and occasionally sha=
med with a splash of red paint. Athenian democracy </span><a href=3D"https:=
//substack.com/redirect/6517135c-2198-43fa-8a47-9faf959d4a66?u=3D16283549" =
rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">worked</a><s=
pan> kind of like very long jury duty, in that each year:&#160;</span></p><=
blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p styl=
e=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;=
 margin-left: 1em;"><em>Each year 500 names were chosen from all the citize=
ns of ancient Athens. Those 500 citizens had to actively serve in the gover=
nment for one year. During that year, they were responsible for making new =
laws and controlled all parts of the political process. When a new law was =
proposed, all the citizens of Athens had the opportunity to vote on it. To =
vote, citizens had to attend the assembly on the day the vote took place.&#=
160;</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>This form of governance, in which =
every citizen can vote on every decision, is called </span><strong>direct d=
emocracy</strong><span>. Every citizen has their say, and then all must fol=
low what the majority decides. Direct democracy worked in Ancient Athens be=
cause the scale was small and local, and even then, the Athenians eliminate=
d 70% of eligible voters (women, slaves, and immigrants) in order to mainta=
in a small group.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Even though the Ancient Greeks i=
ntroduced democracy 2,500 years ago, and Rome remained ruled by a republica=
n government between 500 and 27 BC, autocracy remained the dominant form of=
 governance around the globe, with a few exceptions, until the United State=
s Constitution came into force in 1789.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>But while d=
irect democracy worked well enough in the context of ruling a city, the Ame=
rican experiment required a governance model that could handle 13 colonies =
(and eventually 50 states) spread over a large area. As Hall and Smith </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/74640d1e-a53e-4acf-af50-fa7fee8=
dd3d6?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: unde=
rline;">highlighted</a><span>:&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-=
left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em><sp=
an>As James Madison wrote in </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
t/04964607-681d-45f4-b913-104e8b0e33bd?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"colo=
r: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Federalist No. 14</a><span>, &#822=
0;In a democracy, the people meet and exercise the government in person; in=
 a </span><strong>republic</strong><span>, they assemble and administer it =
by their representatives and agents. A democracy, consequently, will be con=
fined to a small spot. A republic may be extended over a large region.&#822=
1;&#160;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>New contexts require ne=
w forms of governance. America&#8217;s Founding Fathers built a republic, a=
 form of </span><strong>representative democracy. </strong><span>The people=
 elect their representatives, and the representatives propose and pass legi=
slation.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Since then, the world has been on a bumpy=
 but inexorable march towards representative democracy.&#160;</p><div class=
